    "response_text": "Earthquakes are caused by the movement of tectonic plates in the Earth's lithosphere, which is the outermost solid layer of the planet. The lithosphere is broken into several large plates that fit together like a jigsaw puzzle. These plates are in constant motion, sliding over the more fluid asthenosphere below them.\n\nThere are three main types of plate movements that can cause earthquakes:\n\n1.  **Divergent motion**: When two plates move apart from each other, new crust is formed as magma rises up to fill the gap. This process is known as seafloor spreading. As the plates move apart, stress builds up in the Earth's crust, and when it becomes too great, the crust breaks, releasing energy in the form of an earthquake.\n2.  **Convergent motion**: When two plates move towards each other, they can either collide and crumple, or one plate can be forced beneath the other. This process is known as subduction.",
